'''Field goal percentage''' in  is the ''ratio'' of s ''made'' to field goals ''attempted''. Its abbreviation is '''FG%'''. Three-point field goals are included in this percentage. Instead of using scales of 0 to 100%, the scale .000 to 1.000 is commonly used. A higher field goal percentage denotes higher efficiency. In basketball, a FG% of .500 (50%) or above is considered a good percentage, although this criterion does not apply equally to all positions. s usually have lower FG% than s and s. Field goal percentage does not completely tell the skill of a player, but a low field goal percentage can indicate a poor offensive player or a player who takes many difficult shots. In the ,   has a high career FG% (around .580) because he plays near the basket making many high percentage s and s. Guard  often has a low FG% (around .420) because he takes the bulk of his team's shot attempts, even with high difficulty shots.
The NBA career record for field goal percentage is held by  at 0.599.  The highest field goal percentage for a single season was set by  with 0.727 in the 1972-73 season.
 percentage is usually kept as additional statistics. Its abbreviation is '''3FG%'''. A 3FG% of .400 and above is a very good percentage.